    "faqs": [
      {
        "question": "Is the scan painful?",
        "answer": "No. You may feel warmth; loud knocking is normal.\n"
      },
      {
        "question": "How long does it take?",
        "answer": "20–30 minutes for plain scan; 35–40 minutes with contrast.\n"
      },
      {
        "question": "Can I eat before the scan?",
        "answer": "Yes, unless contrast is planned.\n"
      },
      {
        "question": "When will I get my report?",
        "answer": "Same evening for morning slots; next day otherwise.\n"
      },
      {
        "question": "Do I need a doctor’s referral?",
        "answer": "Yes, for insurance; walk-ins accepted for self-pay.\n"
      },
      {
        "question": " What are the main differences between an X-ray and an MRI for the spine?",
        "answer": "X-rays and MRIs are both valuable but show different things:\n        \n   **X-rays:** Show bones. Good for fractures or arthritis. Limited detail on soft tissues like discs, nerves, or marrow.\n        \n   **MRI:** Shows bones and soft tissues. Excellent for discs, cord, nerves, muscles, and subtle bone changes. Usually better for back pain with nerve issues or soft tissue pathology."
      }
    ],
